Review the diff below for SOLID design-principle violations, with Python-specific
judgement. Look for:
  - Single Responsibility: classes/functions/modules doing more than one thing
  - Open/Closed: changes that force editing existing code instead of extending
  - Liskov Substitution: subclasses that break their base contract
  - Interface Segregation: fat interfaces / params forcing unused dependencies
  - Dependency Inversion: high-level code depending on concrete low-level details

Scale strictness to change size; do not invent violations to fill a quota.

